      "earl:test": {
        "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#serverless",
        "dcterms:title": "The SHIPPED Hologram OS is 100% serverless. Its surface is the sealed image (os-closure) + the content-verify Service Worker (holo-fhs-sw.js), served from a dumb static host: the worker is PURE content-routing + Law-L5 re-derivation (both κ axes, refuse-on-mismatch) and carries NO server, proxy, or backend logic. The optional companion backends (SoundCloud/yt-dlp streaming · develop-to-κ · the watch-together room relay · the MCP forwarder · the web proxy) live ONLY in the dev server (tools/holo-serve-fhs.mjs), which is a DEV TOOL — not pinned in the image, not referenced by the worker. So boot, run, resolve and verify need no server (the #boot row proves it boots in real Chromium with zero server fallbacks); the companions are dev-only conveniences a shipped feature degrades gracefully without."
      },
      "earl:result": {
        "@type": "earl:TestResult",
        "earl:outcome": {
          "@id": "earl:failed"
        }
      },
      "earl:mode": {
        "@id": "earl:automatic"
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "earl:Assertion",
      "earl:assertedBy": {
        "@id": "https://hologram.os/tools/gate"
      },
      "earl:subject": {
        "@id": "https://hologram.os",
        "dcterms:title": "Hologram OS"
      },
      "earl:test": {
        "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#self-heal",
        "dcterms:title": "Hologram OS heals itself, autonomously and by content (ADR-0076). A content address is a perfect lie-detector but not a healer — so detection (re-derive every byte, refuse a mismatch, Law L5) is extended with RECOVERY: a corrupted or missing κ-object is re-fetched origin-agnostically from wherever its bytes live (durable κ-store · peers · IPFS · origin, torrent-style) and served ONLY after it re-derives to the SAME address, so a wrong byte from any source is refused and nothing is laundered. A device that heals an object keeps it (seeds it); a proactive idle scrub re-verifies the closure and pre-heals latent corruption before anyone asks, with no user action. Every repair mints a verifiable PROV-O heal receipt (the heal IS witnessed). The supervisor also EVOLVES — verify → refocus → evolve: it learns per-κ flakiness from each sweep's own outcomes (the same repair/miss data the heal-log records) and re-sweeps the historically-unstable objects FIRST, and under a heal-budget more often, while confirming and leaving the stable ones alone; the learned ranking is inspectable (flakiness()) and folded into the health attestation, so 'the OS adapts' is a re-derivable fact, not a claim. The priority signal is REPAIRS (broke-and-recovered, worth re-watching); a MISS (currently unreachable) is tracked but never escalated, so an unresolvable κ cannot monopolise a small heal-budget and starve the objects that can be fixed — staleness rotates it through its fair share. The signal is plain integer history — no clock, no randomness — so the sweep stays deterministic and re-derivation-safe. The sealed ANCHOR — constitution, gate-pinned constants, OS-closure root — is NEVER auto-healed: a broken anchor stays fail-closed and is surfaced to the operator, never rewritten to match drifted bytes."
      },
      "earl:result": {
        "@type": "earl:TestResult",
        "earl:outcome": {
          "@id": "earl:passed"
        }
      },
      "earl:mode": {
        "@id": "earl:automatic"
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "earl:Assertion",
      "earl:assertedBy": {
        "@id": "https://hologram.os/tools/gate"
      },
      "earl:subject": {
        "@id": "https://hologram.os",
        "dcterms:title": "Hologram OS"
      },
      "earl:test": {
        "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#open-web",
        "dcterms:title": "The healer reaches the WHOLE OPEN INTERNET, and proves itself in W3C linked data. The internet is a hypergraph of objects (nodes) addressed by their self-verifying attributes (κ); an HTTPS IRI, an IPFS CIDv1 (a sha-256 κ IS one), a holo:// alias and a did:holo are all EDGES to the same node. The recovery chain follows any edge — the device's durable κ-store, the origin, the object's own W3C DID Core alsoKnownAs HTTPS IRIs, content-address gateways, IPFS Trustless Gateways, and WebRTC-mesh peers — and admits a copy ONLY after it re-derives to the address (Law L5), so fetching from ANY server (a stranger's CDN, a mirror, a gateway) is safe: a wrong or hostile byte loses, the URL is merely a place a copy happens to live. Agents and humans get a first-class importObject(κ | https-URL) → resolve any node from any edge and re-derive it, or fetch an arbitrary web object and content-address it so it joins the substrate — the open web as one address space. And the self-healing artifacts are 100% standards-native: the heal receipt and the health attestation are valid JSON-LD (W3C DID Core + Data Integrity + PROV-O + schema.org @context), content-addressed and re-derivable, and every hosheal: term they mint is DEFINED in a published, dereferenceable OWL ontology (usr/share/ns/heal.jsonld) — mint-nothing, so the open semantic web (humans and agents) can interpret every heal."
      },
      "earl:result": {
        "@type": "earl:TestResult",
        "earl:outcome": {
          "@id": "earl:passed"
        }
      },
      "earl:mode": {
        "@id": "earl:automatic"
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "earl:Assertion",
      "earl:assertedBy": {
