      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "earl:Assertion",
      "earl:assertedBy": {
        "@id": "https://hologram.os/tools/gate"
      },
      "earl:subject": {
        "@id": "https://hologram.os",
        "dcterms:title": "Hologram OS"
      },
      "earl:test": {
        "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#atlas-coordinates",
        "dcterms:title": "Every UOR object has a deterministic, self-verifying COORDINATE in the finite Φ-Atlas-12288 torus (the sealed E8·ATLAS96 object, did:holo:sha256:f82435da…), derived PURELY from its content address (κ) — attribute-derived, re-derivable by anyone from the κ alone (Law L5), and always inside the finite space. The math is verbatim upstream (atlas-12288: Φ(p,b)=(p<<8)|b · R96=b%96 · ℤ₄₈×ℤ₂₅₆=12,288), cross-checked against the sealed object’s own resonator-geometry.js. The content→torus embedding is uniform (objects spread across cells, all 96 R96 classes used). Because the torus is FINITE per level and content-addressing is ACYCLIC, every object is BOTH a point in its parent’s atlas AND itself an atlas for its sub-objects — finite shapes, unbounded depth, no recursion. The canonical shell self-declares its own coordinate. This is an interpretable coordinate NAMESPACE over the object graph — NOT an isolation, storage, compute, or quantum layer (isolation = the W3C sandbox + Law-L5 verify + the conscience gate)."
      },
      "earl:result": {
        "@type": "earl:TestResult",
        "earl:outcome": {
          "@id": "earl:passed"
        }
      },
      "earl:mode": {
        "@id": "earl:automatic"
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "earl:Assertion",
      "earl:assertedBy": {
        "@id": "https://hologram.os/tools/gate"
      },
      "earl:subject": {
        "@id": "https://hologram.os",
        "dcterms:title": "Hologram OS"
      },
      "earl:test": {
        "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#kstore",
        "dcterms:title": "The store IS the memory (Law L3), operational in any browser. The content-addressed κ-store (os/usr/lib/holo/holo-kstore.js) resolves any object BY ITS κ through three tiers — an in-memory Map (sub-µs), OPFS (sub-ms, survives reload), then the κ-route /.holo/<axis>/<hex> over HTTP (cold) — VERIFIED by re-derivation on first fetch (Law L5; a wrong κ is refused, the origin demoted to one untrusted CDN). So the 2nd-and-later open of any object or app is the SUB-MILLISECOND in-memory rebind, not a re-fetch: measured in real Chromium a warm resolve is about 0.5 µs (over 50,000x a cold HTTP+verify), and re-opening a real app rebinds its whole κ-manifest from memory in about 0.2 ms. Each object's atlas coordinate is its content-derived placement (computed, not looked up). This turns a holospace's tiny κ-manifest into a running app by rebind."
      },
      "earl:result": {
        "@type": "earl:TestResult",
        "earl:outcome": {
          "@id": "earl:passed"
        }
      },
      "earl:mode": {
        "@id": "earl:automatic"
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "earl:Assertion",
      "earl:assertedBy": {
        "@id": "https://hologram.os/tools/gate"
      },
      "earl:subject": {
        "@id": "https://hologram.os",
        "dcterms:title": "Hologram OS"
      },
      "earl:test": {
        "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#sw-cache",
        "dcterms:title": "The live app-open path is content-addressed and network-free on re-open. The shell mounts every app as an iframe that fetches its bytes BY PATH through the content-verify Service Worker (os/holo-fhs-sw.js) — a child iframe is a separate browsing context whose subresources the parent page's in-memory arena CANNOT serve, so the SW is the honest live-runtime delivery layer (network-free milliseconds, not the page-side sub-microsecond arena). The worker now VERIFIES app bytes too, not only OS bytes: on the first request under apps/<id>/ it lazily folds that app's own holospace.lock.json closure into its L5 index, so every app byte is re-derived to its pinned κ and a mismatch is refused (a wrong κ on the κ-route is 404 — not in the content index). Verified bytes are then stored in a CacheStorage keyed by κ (/.holo/<axis>/<hex>), so identical bytes are cached ONCE and shared across every app (dedup), and the 2nd-and-later open is served from cache with no origin fetch and no re-hash (x-holo-cache: hit). Measured in real Chromium: a cold open verifies + fills the cache, the warm re-open is network-free at about a quarter the time."
      },
      "earl:result": {
        "@type": "earl:TestResult",
        "earl:outcome": {
          "@id": "earl:passed"
        }
      },
      "earl:mode": {
        "@id": "earl:automatic"
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "earl:Assertion",
      "earl:assertedBy": {
        "@id": "https://hologram.os/tools/gate"
      },
      "earl:subject": {
        "@id": "https://hologram.os",
        "dcterms:title": "Hologram OS"
      },
      "earl:test": {
        "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#runtime-adoption",
        "dcterms:title": "EVERY hologram app takes advantage of the Holo Runtime, and EVERY app self-resolves from its content-derived κ address — so a holo app is shareable by ONE content link that runs fast in any browser. Two things are proven end-to-end. (1) STRUCTURAL, all 34 apps: every app collapses to a single content-derived ROOT κ (its whole self-describing identity — the thing a link carries), every entry in its closure is κ-pinned (no app byte is trusted by location), and a sampled leaf of every app RE-DERIVES to its pinned κ (the bytes hash to their address — Law L5), so each app self-resolves from content, not path. (2) LIVE, a representative sample (files · notepad · wallet · search · git · forge) driven in real Chromium: each is delivered through the ONE content-verify Holo Runtime Service Worker with no per-app opt-in (the gateway registers it at root scope, so every nested app inherits it); each app's first open verifies + fills the κ-cache and its SECOND open is NETWORK-FREE from the κ-keyed content cache (x-holo-cache: hit — the ultra-low-latency advantage); each app's index SELF-RESOLVES on the κ-route (the bytes returned for its κ match), and a wrong κ is refused. No app was modified to gain this — adoption is universal and automatic because delivery and addressing are the runtime's, not each app's."
      },
      "earl:result": {
        "@type": "earl:TestResult",
        "earl:outcome": {
          "@id": "earl:failed"
        }
      },
      "earl:mode": {
        "@id": "earl:automatic"
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "earl:Assertion",
      "earl:assertedBy": {
        "@id": "https://hologram.os/tools/gate"
      },
      "earl:subject": {
        "@id": "https://hologram.os",
        "dcterms:title": "Hologram OS"
      },
      "earl:test": {
        "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#share-runtime",
        "dcterms:title": "An existing holo app is shareable by ONE content link that always opens and runs on the ultra-low-latency Holo Runtime — proven literally, the Telegram path. The share link the shell emits (holospace.html?app=<ref>#k=<κ>, the Share-to-Run convention, ADR-064) is opened in a COLD, fresh browser context — no cache, no service worker, no prior visit, exactly what happens when someone taps a link from a chat app on a device that has never seen the origin. It must, and does: (1) OPEN and RENDER the app fullscreen with the Share-to-Run chrome (the app actually paints in its sandboxed frame — measured cold in real Chromium in a few hundred ms); (2) SELF-RESOLVE the app by its content address (the app's bytes return from the κ-route and match its κ); (3) run on the ONE Holo Runtime delivery worker (holo-fhs-sw.js — the κ-keyed content cache + app-byte L5 verification), the SAME runtime as the rest of the OS — the share path was unified onto it (it no longer uses a separate per-app worker), so a shared app is content-verified and the runtime's, not bare HTTP; (4) the SECOND open is NETWORK-FREE from the κ-cache (x-holo-cache: hit). One link, any browser, no install, no account, no server — opens fast, runs verified, re-opens network-free."
      },
      "earl:result": {
        "@type": "earl:TestResult",
        "earl:outcome": {
          "@id": "earl:passed"
        }
      },
      "earl:mode": {
        "@id": "earl:automatic"
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "earl:Assertion",
      "earl:assertedBy": {
        "@id": "https://hologram.os/tools/gate"
      },
      "earl:subject": {
        "@id": "https://hologram.os",
        "dcterms:title": "Hologram OS"
      },
      "earl:test": {
        "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#pretty-link",
        "dcterms:title": "An external share address can be SHORT, ATTRACTIVE and self-verifying at once — without breaking decentralized interoperability. The principle: the name is a hint, the κ is the truth. (1) SHORTER + standard: a κ (did:holo:sha256:<64 hex>, 80 chars) is spelled as a CIDv1 (os/usr/lib/holo/holo-cid.mjs — multibase base32 · multicodec raw · sha2-256, ~59 chars, bafkrei…), the exact same digest in the envelope the whole content-addressing ecosystem speaks (IPFS · IPLD), so it is shorter AND more interoperable; it round-trips losslessly back to the identical κ (proven for every sampled app). (2) CLEANER: a /~<app>#k=<cid> route replaces holospace.html?app=…#k=did:holo:… — the path is a human hint, the #k= CID is the content handle. (3) PRETTIER: the route serves a per-app Open Graph card a chat crawler reads from static HTML (og:title · og:image · summary_large_image), and the og:image is a DETERMINISTIC, content-derived κ-identicon (os/usr/lib/holo/holo-identicon.mjs — the colour and glyph come straight from the digest, so the picture re-derives exactly like the address; same κ → same picture, distinct per app). INTEROP PRESERVED: nothing is resolved without the κ re-deriving — the CID losslessly carries the content address, the served app bytes are re-derived by the runtime worker (Law L5), and any shortener/name resolver is untrusted-by-construction (a lie is refused). Proven live in a cold browser: the clean CID link opens + renders the app on the Holo Runtime worker, and the CID decodes to the app's real κ. (Honest boundary: the dev server injects per-app OG meta to prove the mechanism; a static host needs the build to pre-render per-app /~<app> pages, or host templating — the CID, the clean route, and a generic card work on any host.)"
      },
      "earl:result": {
        "@type": "earl:TestResult",
        "earl:outcome": {
          "@id": "earl:passed"
        }
      },
      "earl:mode": {
        "@id": "earl:automatic"
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "earl:Assertion",
      "earl:assertedBy": {
        "@id": "https://hologram.os/tools/gate"
      },
      "earl:subject": {
        "@id": "https://hologram.os",
        "dcterms:title": "Hologram OS"
      },
      "earl:test": {
        "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#runtime",
        "dcterms:title": "The Holo Runtime is the SINGLE canonical native runtime for every hologram app (os/lib/holo-runtime.mjs). It is the second of the three tiers — holospace shell (the OS frame) · Holo Runtime (the core every app inherits) · the apps themselves — and it lives exactly once at os/usr/lib/holo, reached by every app through the flat /_shared/ URL space that the ONE flat→FHS map (lib/holo-fhs-map.mjs) routes there. No engine is duplicated between the runtime and any app bundle (an app's own _shared/ may carry only app-only engines with no runtime master). Beyond 'shared engines live here once', the runtime DECLARES the substrate capabilities every app inherits as one definition: the content-addressed STORE (holo-kstore.js — resolve any object by its κ through a contiguous in-memory arena that earns L1/L2 residency by locality → OPFS → the κ-route, verified by re-derivation, Law L5); the content-verify DELIVERY wire (holo-fhs-sw.js — re-derives every byte, OS and app alike by folding each app's own lock into its L5 index, refuses a wrong κ, and serves verified bytes from a κ-keyed CacheStorage so the 2nd open is network-free and deduped across apps; registered at root scope by the gateway so every nested app inherits it with no per-app wiring — the honest live-runtime re-open path, since a child iframe is a separate context the page-side arena cannot serve); and the content-derived ADDRESSING axes (the σ-axis BLAKE3 ≡ the upstream kappa(), and the finite Φ-Atlas-12288 coordinate). Each capability lives once and is BOUND by apps, never reimplemented (Law L2), and its behavioral guarantees rest on the proven #kstore and #sw-cache rows."
      },
      "earl:result": {
        "@type": "earl:TestResult",
        "earl:outcome": {
          "@id": "earl:passed"
        }
      },
      "earl:mode": {
