      "earl:test": {
        "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#share-to-run",
        "dcterms:title": "Share-to-Run — the growth loop (ADR-064): a SHARED holospace link (one carrying #k= provenance) lands a GUEST fullscreen in the running app, with an OS-level chrome laid OVER the app's sandboxed frame (so the substrate speaks, not the app) — run it, REMIX it (one tap to your own editable copy in the World shell), SHARE it (the content-addressed link, no sign-in), SAVE it (the pull to create your self-sovereign Space, never a gate before value). The chrome shows the app's VERIFIED content address (κ, re-derived not URL-trusted), is contextual to shared landings only (a bare kiosk link stays clean), rides the canonical --holo-* tokens + the readability floor, and honors prefers-reduced-motion. The native, private-first viral loop (share-to-run-to-remix) over the content-addressed substrate — no central feed, no parallel infrastructure (Law L1/L4). The loop SELF-seeds from EVERY creation surface: both the World shell's Share (its modal · QR · Copy all carry it) AND the in-app Manage panel emit this magic link, so a creator's first share lands the recipient in the chrome (the frame resolves the link by content address OR by the app's served-path id). Proven by driving the whole loop in real Chromium (13 checks — shared landing renders, kiosk stays clean, the World shell Share AND the Manage panel each emit the magic link, a path-built link resolves and lands in the chrome, and that link lands the next guest back in the chrome: the loop closed end-to-end)"
      },
