      },
      "earl:test": {
        "@id": "https://hologram.os/conformance/os2#atlas96-resonator",
        "dcterms:title": "The Atlas 96 Resonator is the Φ-Atlas-12288 boundary made PHYSICAL, AUDIBLE and PROVABLE — the whole 12,288-cell torus (T² = ℤ₄₈ × ℤ₂₅₆, verbatim upstream invariants: R96 = b % 96 · Φ(p,b) = (p << 8) | b) as an interactive fiber instrument: pull a cell, field-grab the whole structure, squeeze it until it buckles, pluck it; morph the SAME cells through 1D cycle → 2D sheet → 3D torus → 4D Clifford torus in S³; hear deformation as 96-EDO partials over the R96 classes (class c sounds at 220·2^(c/96) Hz) with truth ≙ conservation (the strain budget returns to 0). Its structure is NOT parametric — every irregular artifact of the weave (each fiber kink, each hole) is a byte of DNA(p,b) = SHA-256(atlasObjectId ‖ Φ(p,b)), zero free parameters, zero RNG, sealed in a PROV-O receipt and re-derived LIVE in the tab (Law L5); tampering ONE codepoint of the atlas object is refused with all 12,288 cells re-deriving differently. It is 100% BROWSER-NATIVE and HARDWARE-MAXIMAL: the atlas engine itself (R96 · Φ · truth) is COMPILED IN THE TAB by Holo Forge from the verbatim upstream C and verified against its sealed build receipt — five live re-derivations in total; the structure is derived once, content-addressed, and REBOUND O(1) by κ on every later visit (with a full background re-derivation, so O(1) never weakens the proof); the physics lives on the user's GPU — a WebGPU compute tier (Jacobi PBD over all cells and constraints in WGSL, storage-buffer instanced fibers, zero per-frame CPU geometry) with the WebGL2 tier as the verified fallback — and the renderer adapts to the hardware's real headroom up to an 8K-class backbuffer. This is the decidable answer to 'how do we know the model didn't just classify the shape and apply the math formula — did the mesh capture the specific, irregular artifacts?': re-derive, or be refused"
      },
